# Introduction

The main concern in designing a network visualization is the purpose it has to serve. What are the structural properties that we want to highlight? What are the key concerns we want to address?

![](https://sds-aau.github.io/SDS-master/00_media/networks_viz_goal.png){width=500px}

Network maps are far from the only visualization available for graphs - other network representation formats, and even simple charts of key characteristics, may be more appropriate in some cases.

![](https://sds-aau.github.io/SDS-master/00_media/networks_viz_type.png){width=500px}

In network maps, as in other visualization formats, we have several key elements that control the outcome. The major ones are color, size, shape, and position.

![](https://sds-aau.github.io/SDS-master/00_media/networks_viz_controls.png?dl=1){width=500px}

# Visualization Basics


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
# We load the highschool network nd make up som characteristics
set.seed(1337)
g <- as_tbl_graph(highschool, directed = TRUE) %E>%
  mutate(weight = sample(1:5, n(), replace = TRUE),
         year = year %>% as.factor()) %N>%
  mutate(class = sample(LETTERS[1:3], n(), replace = TRUE),
         gender = rbinom(n = n(), size = 1, prob = 0.5) %>% as.logical(),
         label = randomNames::randomNames(gender = gender, name.order = "first.last"))
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g <- g %N>%
  mutate(community = group_edge_betweenness(weights = weight, directed = TRUE) %>% as.factor()) %N>%
  filter(!node_is_isolated()) %E>%
  mutate(community_from = .N()$community[from],
         community_to = .N()$community[to])
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

## Node Visualization

* Nodes in a network are the entities that are connected. Sometimes these are also referred to as vertices. 
* While the nodes in a graph are the abstract concepts of entities, and the layout is their physical placement, the node geoms are the visual manifestation of the entities. 

### Node positions

* Conceptually one can simply think of it in terms of a scatter plot â€” the layout provides the x and y coordinates, and these can be used to draw nodes in different ways in the plotting window. 
* Actually, due to the design of ggraph the standard scatterplot-like geoms from ggplot2 can be used directly for plotting nodes:


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lXG4gIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSBcIm5pY2VseVwiKSArIFxuICAgIGdlb21fcG9pbnQoYWVzKHggPSB4LCB5ID0geSkpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>%
  ggraph(layout = "nicely") + 
    geom_point(aes(x = x, y = y))
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


* The reason this works is that layouts (about which we talk in a moment) return a `data.frame` of node positions and metadata and this is used as the default plot data:


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGNyZWF0ZV9sYXlvdXQobGF5b3V0ID0gXCJuaWNlbHlcIikgJT4lIGhlYWQoKVxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% create_layout(layout = "nicely") %>% head()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

* While usage of the default `ggplot2` is theoreticlly fine, `ggraph` practically comes with its own set of node geoms (`geom_node_*()`). 
* They by default already inherit the layout x and y coordinates, and come with extra features for network visualization.
* `ggraph` also comes with an own plotting theme (`theme_graph()`), which optimizes for graph visualization, and we might want to use.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9ub2RlX3BvaW50KCkgK1xuICB0aGVtZV9ncmFwaCgpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_node_point() +
  theme_graph()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


* Usually (but not always) when visualizing a network, we are interested in the connectivity structure as expressed by the interplay between nodes and edges. 
* So, lets also plot the edges (the geometries from the `geom_edge_*` family, about which we talk in a moment)


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9ub2RlX3BvaW50KCkgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9lZGdlX2xpbmsoYWxwaGEgPSAwLjI1KSArXG4gIHRoZW1lX2dyYXBoKClcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_node_point() + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) +
  theme_graph()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

### Size

* Size is the first obvious choice to highlight important (eg. central) nodes on a contineous scale.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9lZGdlX2xpbmsoYWxwaGEgPSAwLjI1KSArXG4gIGdlb21fbm9kZV9wb2ludChhZXMoc2l6ZSA9IGNlbnRyYWxpdHlfZGVncmVlKCkpKSArXG4gIHRoZW1lX2dyYXBoKClcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_point(aes(size = centrality_degree())) +
  theme_graph()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

### Labels

* With the `geom_node_text` geometry, we can also ad labels to the node. They are subject to common aestetics.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9lZGdlX2xpbmsoYWxwaGEgPSAwLjI1KSArXG4gIGdlb21fbm9kZV90ZXh0KGFlcyhsYWJlbCA9IGxhYmVsKSkgK1xuICB0aGVtZV9ncmFwaCgpIFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = label)) +
  theme_graph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


In large graphs, plotting labels can appear messy, so it might make sense to only focus on important nodes to label


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9lZGdlX2xpbmsoYWxwaGEgPSAwLjI1KSArXG4gIGdlb21fbm9kZV9wb2ludCgpICtcbiAgZ2VvbV9ub2RlX3RleHQoYWVzKGxhYmVsID0gbGFiZWwpLCByZXBlbCA9IFRSVUUpICtcbiAgdGhlbWVfZ3JhcGgoKSBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_point() +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = label), repel = TRUE) +

```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


* Still looks like too much. If we want to highlight only certain important nodes with label, we can also only plot them.
* Note that (very practical) all `ggraph` geoms have a `filter` aestetic we can use for that



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_point() +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = label, 
                     filter = centrality_degree() >= centrality_degree()  %>% quantile(0.9)), 
                 repel = TRUE) +
  theme_graph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


### Combined node visualization tools


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_point(aes(size = centrality_eigen(), 
                      color = community,
                      shape = gender)) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = label, 
                     filter = centrality_eigen() >= centrality_eigen() %>% quantile(0.90)), 
                 repel = TRUE) +
  theme_graph() +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

## Edge Visualization

* So, now that we captured nodes, lets see how we can highlight aspects of edges, which are visualized with the geometries of the `geom_edge_*` family.

### Weight

* Obviously, the edge weight (=thickness)


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9lZGdlX2xpbmsoYWVzKHNpemUgPSB3ZWlnaHQpLCBhbHBoYSA9IDAuMjUpICtcbiAgZ2VvbV9ub2RlX3BvaW50KCkgK1xuICB0aGVtZV9ncmFwaCgpIFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(aes(size = weight), alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_point() +
  theme_graph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


### Color

* Color can also be used to 
Notice, since we want to represent the colors of potentially multiple edges between a node pair, I now use the `geom_edge_fan` geometry.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTMzNylcbmcgJT4lIGdncmFwaChsYXlvdXQgPSAnbmljZWx5JykgKyBcbiAgZ2VvbV9lZGdlX2ZhbihhZXMoc2l6ZSA9IHdlaWdodCxcbiAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgICAgIGNvbG9yID0geWVhciksIGFscGhhID0gMC4yNSkgK1xuICBnZW9tX25vZGVfcG9pbnQoKSArXG4gIHRoZW1lX2dyYXBoKCkgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_fan(aes(size = weight,
                     color = year), alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_node_point() +
  theme_graph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


### Density


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_edge_density(aes(fill = year)) +
  geom_node_point(aes(size = cent_dgr, 
                      color = community,
                      shape = gender),
                  show.legend = FALSE) +
  theme_graph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


### Directionality

The easiestb way to express directionality is by defining the `arrow()`, which comes with own aestetics.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
g %>% ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_fan(aes(size = weight,
                    color = year,
                    shape = year), 
                arrow = arrow(type = "closed", length = unit(2, "mm")),
                start_cap = circle(1, "mm"),
                end_cap = circle(1, "mm"),
                alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_node_point(aes(size = cent_dgr, 
                      color = community, 
                      shape = gender),
                  show.legend = FALSE) +
  theme_graph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Another nice trick is to work with alphas or colors, which change between start and end node.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->

```r
g %>%
  ggraph(layout = 'nicely') + 
  geom_edge_fan(aes(size = weight,
                    color = community_from, # Notice that
                    shape = year,
                    alpha = stat(index)) # Notice that
                ) +
  geom_node_point(aes(size = cent_dgr, 
                      color = community,
                      shape = gender),
                  show.legend = FALSE) +
  theme_graph() + 
  scale_edge_alpha("Edge direction", guide = "edge_direction")
```
